-## 1. Scorer — Rate Engrams
+## 1. Framing
 
-The Scorer trait rates Engrams along multi-dimensional axes (see
-[03-score-7-axis-appraisal.md](03-score-7-axis-appraisal.md)). Scorers are pure functions
-of `(Engram, Context)` — no side effects, no I/O, no state mutation.
+Roko's kernel now has two mediums and two fabrics:
 
-### 1.1 Trait Signature
+- `Engram` is the durable medium.
+- `Pulse` is the ephemeral medium.
+- `Substrate` is the storage fabric.
+- `Bus` is the transport fabric.
+
+The five operators in this document work over those mediums through a shared `Datum` enum when polymorphism is useful. They sit beside the two fabric traits rather than replacing them, so the kernel remains six operations plus two fabric traits even though only these five non-fabric operators need signature updates here.
+
+`Datum` is the bridge type:
+
+```rust
+pub enum Datum<'a> {
+    Engram(&'a Engram),
+    Pulse(&'a Pulse),
+}
+```
+
+The practical rule is simple:
+
+- Use `Engram` when the operation is about durable records.
+- Use `Pulse` when the operation is about live transport or stream windows.
+- Use `Datum` when the same operator should accept either shape without introducing a new trait.
+
+This document treats legacy names only as historical context. User-facing prose uses `Engram`, `Pulse`, `Bus`, `Substrate`, `Topic`, and `Datum`.
+
+---
+
+## 2. Scorer - Rate Either Medium
+
+The Scorer trait measures quality, relevance, or utility. Most score functions are naturally defined over Engrams, but stream chunks and transport records can also be scored when the system needs live calibration.
+
+### 2.1 Recommended Signature
 
 ```rust
 pub trait Scorer: Send + Sync {
-    fn score(&self, signal: &Signal, ctx: &Context) -> Score;
-    fn name(&self) -> &'static str { "unnamed_scorer" }
+    fn score_engram(&self, e: &Engram, ctx: &Context) -> Score;
+
+    fn score_pulse(&self, p: &Pulse, ctx: &Context) -> Score {
+        let synthetic = p.to_synthetic_engram();
+        self.score_engram(&synthetic, ctx)
+    }
+
+    fn score(&self, datum: Datum<'_>, ctx: &Context) -> Score {
+        match datum {
+            Datum::Engram(e) => self.score_engram(e, ctx),
+            Datum::Pulse(p) => self.score_pulse(p, ctx),
+        }
+    }
+
+    fn name(&self) -> &'static str;
 }
 ```
 
-### 1.2 Key Implementations
+### 2.2 Why This Shape
+
+`score_engram` remains the fast path for durable records. `score_pulse` gives stream-aware scorers a native hook, while the default conversion path keeps simple implementations small. The top-level `score(Datum)` method is the polymorphic entry point used by operators that do not want to branch at the call site.
 
-| Scorer | What It Measures | Primary Axis |
-|---|---|---|
-| `RelevanceScorer` | Semantic match to current goal (via Context.goal) | confidence |
-| `RecencyScorer` | How recent the Engram is | confidence (decreasing with age) |
-| `ReputationScorer` | Author's historical track record | reputation |
-| `CatalyticScorer` | How many downstream Engrams this enabled | utility |
-| `KeywordOverlapScorer` | Keyword match between Engram and query | confidence |
-| `ToolRelevanceScorer` | How relevant a tool is to the current task | confidence |
-| `CompositeScorer` | Weighted combination of multiple Scorers | all axes |
+This matches the REF04 rule: the trait stays the same, but the method surface becomes medium-aware.
 
-### 1.3 Composition
+### 2.3 Typical Uses
 
-Multiple Scorers compose into a pipeline via `CompositeScorer`, which applies weighted
-combinations using Score arithmetic (addition for evidence aggregation, multiplication for
-modifier application).
+- `RelevanceScorer` scores an Engram against the current goal.
+- `RecencyScorer` scores an Engram by age and decay.
+- `StreamHealthScorer` scores a Pulse stream chunk for anomaly detection.
+- `ToolRelevanceScorer` scores live transport data when routing or gating depends on current activity.
 
-### 1.4 Scorer as Parameter
+### 2.4 Composition
 
-The Composer trait takes `&dyn Scorer` as an argument, enabling the same Composer to produce
-different outputs based on which scoring function is injected. This is the key composition
-point between L2 (Scaffold) scoring and L2 context assembly.
+Scorers still compose through `CompositeScorer`. The composition model does not change; only the admissible input shapes expand.
 
